{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-article-tsx","path":"/torque/","result":{"data":{"markdownRemark":{"html":"<h1>Torque</h1>\n<p><strong>Torque</strong> (<span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>τ</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\tau</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.1132em;\">τ</span></span></span></span>) is force that causes an object to rotate around an axis and is measured in joules (<span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>J</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">J</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.09618em;\">J</span></span></span></span>). Formally, torque is force (<span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>F</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">F</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span></span></span></span>) times distance (<span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>d</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">d</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.69444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">d</span></span></span></span>), or <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>τ</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>F</mi><mi>d</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\tau=Fd</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.1132em;\">τ</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.69444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">d</span></span></span></span>. Though torque's definition is very similar to <a href=\"../physics/\">work</a> and the units of measure are the same, it is <em>not</em> work because work by definition causes <em>displacement</em> which is linear whereas torque by definition causes <em>rotation</em>.</p>\n<p>By convention, Torque is negative when the rotation is clockwise and positive when rotation is counter-clockwise.</p>\n<h2>Resources to Learn About Torque</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://www.khanacademy.org/science/physics/torque-angular-momentum/torque-tutorial/v/introduction-to-torque\">Khan Academy: Introduction to Torque</a></li>\n</ul>","fields":{"slug":"/torque/"},"frontmatter":{"title":"Torque","tags":["physics","angular-motion"]}}},"pageContext":{"slug":"/torque/"}},"staticQueryHashes":["2270328656","3794076007","80858887"]}